          "id": 8,
          "question": "<p><a name=\"8281\"></a><div itemprop=\"text\"><p>Suppose \\( L = \\left\\{ p, q, r, s, t\\right\\} \\) is a lattice represented by the following Hasse diagram:</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"images/gateOverFlowPDFsImages/volume1/discrete_mathematics_set_theory_algebra_lattice/a35d78ccf3fd6a31fcb30d764a106bce.png\"></p>\n\n<p>For any \\( x, y \\in L \\), not necessarily distinct , \\( x \\vee y \\) and \\( x \\wedge y \\) are join and meet of \\( x, y \\), respectively. Let \\( L^3&nbsp;= \\left\\{\\left(x, y, z\\right): x, y, z \\in L\\right\\} \\) be the set of all ordered triplets of the elements of \\( L \\). Let \\( p_{r} \\) be the probability that an element \\( \\left(x, y,z\\right) \\in L^3 \\)&nbsp;chosen equiprobably satisfies \\( x \\vee (y \\wedge z) = (x \\vee &nbsp;y) \\wedge (x \\vee &nbsp;z) \\). Then</p>\n\n</div><br><br><b>GATE CSE 2015 Set 1 | Question: 34</b></p>",
          "type": "single",
          "options": [
            "<p>\\( p_r = 0 \\)</p>",
            "<p>\\( p_r = 1 \\)</p>",
            "<p>\\( 0 &lt; p_r&nbsp;≤ \\frac{1}{5} \\)</p>",
            "<p>\\( \\frac{1}{5} &lt; p_r &lt; 1 \\)</p>"
          ],
          "correct_answer": "<p>\\( \\frac{1}{5} &lt; p_r &lt; 1 \\)</p>",
          "marks": 1,
          "negative_marks": 0.33,
          "explanation": "<p><a href=\"https://gateoverflow.in/8281/gate-cse-2015-set-1-question-34\" target=\"_blank\">https://gateoverflow.in/8281/gate-cse-2015-set-1-question-34</a></p>"
        },
